<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY: BANKING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 FDIC Loosens Appraisal Rules: The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. said it will 
no longer require banks to make appraisals for real estate loans of less than 
$250,000. The previous limit was $100,000.The agency made the change in an 
effort to make home loans easier to obtain and to cut lenders' red tape, but 
appraisers warned that it could lead to an increase in the number of bad loans 
and create a 1980s-style banking crisis. The FDIC's new rule won't save many 
consumers money, some lenders said, because it does not apply to thrifts and 
because the Federal National Mortgage Assn. and most other companies that buy 
notes from lenders on the secondary market still require appraisals for all the 
loans they purchase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
