<HEADLINE>
<P>
CRACKED WINDSHIELD FORCES JET BACK TO S.F. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The windshield on a New York-bound passenger jet cracked half an hour after 
takeoff Tuesday, but the plane returned to the airport without incident. 
</P>
<P>
 Delta Flight 96 took off from San Francisco International Airport at 11 a.m. 
and was flying at 30,000 feet when cracks suddenly appeared on the outer 
lamination of the pilot-side windshield. 
</P>
<P>
 "There was rapid spider-web cracking," said airport spokesman Ron Wilson. "The 
crew said you could hear it -- it was somewhat frightening." 
</P>
<P>
 Nothing had hit the plane, the crew reported. 
</P>
<P>
 The pilot dropped the Boeing 767 to 10,000 feet and turned around to San 
Francisco, where the plane landed about noon, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA050494-0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 038489 </DOCID>
